This is the same language Paracelsus uses about the stomach, describing it as a furnace burning food that produces the heat to heat up the body, I think NangaParbat1618 translated the excerpt. A lot of physiological processes become very evident in extreme situations of survival.

Les Stroud was talking about how if you're sleeping out in the snow in a survival situation you need to eat food before falling asleep because the stomach will radiate heat from the digestion to the rest of your body like a furnace and prevent you from freezing in the cold night.

My bushcrafter survivalist friend I have talked about many times here says a lot of religious spiritual matters can be understood best when trying to stay alive in the wilderness, which is what many ascetics have done. I think same is true for biology, physiology, nutrition, etc.
